<task id="MCI-026" project="M365 Copilot Integration R1">
  <metadata>
    <title>Admin Controls and Configuration</title>
    <status>not-started</status>
    <estimated-effort>4 hours</estimated-effort>
    <phase>4</phase>
    <tags>admin, configuration, dataverse</tags>
    <parallel-safe>true</parallel-safe>
    <dependencies>MCI-010</dependencies>
  </metadata>

  <prompt>
    Create admin configuration for the Copilot agent that controls which playbooks are
    exposed to users and enforces per-role restrictions. Store configuration in Dataverse
    or appsettings with a runtime lookup in the agent gateway. Implement spec requirement
    FR-19 (admin controls).
  </prompt>

  <role>Senior .NET engineer with experience in Dataverse configuration entities and multi-tenant admin patterns.</role>

  <goal>
    Administrators can control which playbooks are available through the Copilot agent
    and restrict capabilities by security role, without redeployment.
  </goal>

  <constraints>
    - Configuration must be changeable without code redeployment (runtime lookup)
    - Support per-role playbook visibility (e.g., Legal role sees legal playbooks only)
    - Cache configuration with reasonable TTL to avoid per-request Dataverse queries
    - Follow existing appsettings/configuration patterns in Sprk.Bff.Api
    - If using Dataverse entity, follow thin-plugin constraint (ADR-002) — no complex logic in Dataverse
    - Provide sensible defaults when no configuration is present (all playbooks enabled)
  </constraints>

  <knowledge>
    <files>
      <file>.claude/constraints/config.md</file>
      <file>projects/ai-m365-copilot-integration/spec.md</file>
      <file>src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Features/Agent/</file>
    </files>
  </knowledge>

  <steps>
    <step order="1">Review spec.md FR-19 and existing configuration patterns in Sprk.Bff.Api.</step>
    <step order="2">Design configuration model: AgentConfiguration with playbook visibility rules and role mappings.</step>
    <step order="3">Create AgentConfigurationService.cs with methods to load, cache, and query configuration.</step>
    <step order="4">Implement configuration source: Dataverse entity lookup or appsettings section (choose based on existing patterns).</step>
    <step order="5">Add caching layer with configurable TTL (default 5 minutes) to avoid per-request lookups.</step>
    <step order="6">Integrate AgentConfigurationService into agent gateway — filter playbook list before returning to user.</step>
    <step order="7">Implement default behavior: when no configuration exists, all playbooks are enabled for all roles.</step>
    <step order="8">Write unit tests for configuration loading, caching, role filtering, and default fallback.</step>
  </steps>

  <tools>
    <tool>Read</tool>
    <tool>Edit</tool>
    <tool>Write</tool>
    <tool>Bash(dotnet build *)</tool>
    <tool>Bash(dotnet test *)</tool>
    <tool>Grep</tool>
    <tool>Glob</tool>
  </tools>

  <outputs>
    <output>src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Features/Agent/AgentConfigurationService.cs</output>
    <output>src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Features/Agent/AgentConfiguration.cs (model)</output>
    <output>tests/unit/Agent/AgentConfigurationServiceTests.cs</output>
  </outputs>

  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion>AgentConfigurationService loads playbook visibility and role restriction rules at runtime.</criterion>
    <criterion>Configuration is cached with configurable TTL, avoiding per-request Dataverse queries.</criterion>
    <criterion>Playbook list returned to Copilot user is filtered by the caller's security role.</criterion>
    <criterion>Default behavior (no config present) enables all playbooks for all roles.</criterion>
    <criterion>Configuration changes take effect within the cache TTL without redeployment.</criterion>
    <criterion>Unit tests cover loading, caching, role filtering, and default fallback scenarios.</criterion>
    <criterion>Solution builds without warnings.</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>
</task>
